  "prompt": "Is it true that most of the people who won the lottery eventually filed for bankruptcy?",
  "response": "While there are several studies and reports suggesting that lottery winners are more likely to experience financial difficulties, the claim that \"most\" lottery winners file for bankruptcy is somewhat exaggerated. \n\nSome research, like a 2010 study by Mark Hoekstra, found that lottery winners are more likely to declare bankruptcy within five years compared to the general population. However, this doesn't mean that most winners go bankrupt.\n\nThe main factors contributing to financial problems among lottery winners include:\n1. Sudden wealth syndrome\n2. Poor financial management\n3. Excessive spending\n4. Lack of financial planning\n5. Pressure from friends and family\n6. Unrealistic lifestyle expectations\n\nTo avoid financial pitfalls, lottery winners are often advised to:\n- Seek professional financial advice\n- Create a comprehensive financial plan\n- Invest wisely\n- Maintain a budget\n- Keep their winnings private\n- Avoid making drastic lifestyle changes immediately\n\nWhile some lottery winners do face financial challenges, it would be inaccurate to say that \"most\" eventually file for bankruptcy.",
